english:
  title: The Great Granary
  author: Jeong Mongju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The recluse cannot sleep through the night.
    Autumn's breath sweeps chill through the darkness.
    At dawn, I gaze upon the courtyard trees—
    branches and leaves already half turned gold.

    White clouds drift in from the east,
    and my thoughts stretch toward my native land.
    But my homeland lies ten thousand leagues away,
    and return remains forever beyond my grasp.

    I take an ancient sage's book in hand.
    When sorrow comes, I seek solace in its pages.
    Yet sorrow winds through my very bowels,
    and I cast the book down with a long sigh.

    Human life spans but a hundred years—
    light and shadow pass like a crack in time.
    Why then do I not find peace within myself?
    Why have I become a wanderer in distant lands?
  footnotes:
    - The 'recluse' (유인) may refer to the poet himself in a moment of contemplation and withdrawal
    - The 'ancient sage's book' likely refers to classical Chinese philosophy, which Jeong Mongju would have studied deeply
    - The poem's exploration of homesickness and the transience of life reflects themes common in Korean Confucian literati poetry
